title: For Sale:  4-pack AR-15 Bullet Button Tool Magazine Easy Release Kits *Price included shipping*
postcontent:
No more having to swap hands to reload. No more keeping a bullet or other tool in your pocket. No more having your tool slip off your finger or squeeze it too hard. No more getting your leg wacked by a tool attached to a retractable chain. Most importantly, no more accidentally committing a felony by leaving your tool attached to your bullet button. 

The tool mounts to "virtually any" stamped aluminum or plastic magazine. The cap is made from plastic to help protect your AR-15 from scratches and it can be replaced if its damaged or wears out. This simple to use system is a "MUST SEE" for any bullet button AR user. 

All research done on the CA DOJ website, as well as feedback from gun shop owners, parts dealers, and contributors to previous Calguns.net threads, indicate that this tool complies with CA DOJ regulations. What makes it compliant is that once a modified magazine is inserted into the mag-well it becomes part of the rifle, rendering the tool "unusable". It still requires another modified magazine (or other tool) to remove the magazine from the rifle. However, it is not officially approved by CA DOJ.

Package included: 
4 x Alloy Steel Screw
4 x Black Plastic Cap
1 x L Hex Key
(No Magazines included)
*Payment via Paypal, Price included shippping*

These self-install kits allow you to place a bullet button release tip at the base of your magazines.  
Works for most Polymer Magazine.

This is a proven game getting rig.  If you're not familiar, go to www.drawloc.com or go to youtube and search for Hickory Creek Inline Crossbow Draw-Loc.

This particular "vertical crossbow" / Draw-Loc rig is a 2011 manufacture "23 Magnum" bow, which is a 23" ATA bow, with the newer more advanced bullpup draw-loc trigger system - it has an excellent trigger.

It is an 85 lb draw weight, according to Jerry at Hickory Creek, yet is very easy to cock and un-cock by hand - no need to use any kind of rope or crank to cock - even a teenage kid can easily do it.  

If you need to change ambush spots or when you're done hunting, no need to shoot a bolt or arrow - just un-cock by hand.  It has an anti-dry-fire device which I have disassembled and removed from the "arm" (in order to use FOBs) but I will put back on for you if you like, or simply ship it with the parts to later add it back on.  

This bow is tuned and uses regular arrows.  I've been using Easton FMJ 340s with it, at around 28".  Arrows do not come with this bow, however.  It DOES come with a tuned G5 "Expert" fall-away rest, so you can use feathers or FOBs if you want.  It also comes with the shown rubbery stabilizer (pretty decent one).  Not many Draw-Loc rigs or crossbows have a working fall-away rest like this one.

The finish on the black riser is pretty nicked up, but doesn't affect function.  The camo limbs look great.  The string is pretty decent, but will need to be replaced before too long.  The string length is 74 & 3/4th" and the cable length is 25 1/2".  Could probably get at least a season or two more yet out of this string.

It has a 4-Pin I.Q. Bowsight with "retina lock". I have removed the built-in aluminum cocking stirrup that came on the 23 magnum.   But it's easy to simply place your feet against the riser to cock it, while sitting on the ground or in a chair - that's what I do.  The removal of this integral cocking stirrup saves weight, which is why I did it.  You can order a cocking stirrup from Hickory Creek if you really feel you need to cock it while standing for some reason.

https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=hickory+creek+draw-loc

I paid around $800 for this bow with the bullpup arm, not counting the accessories.  
Prices Shown INCLUDE shipping to your door anywhere in the lower 48, and reflect a discount due to removing the cocking stirrup:

--$495 with everything
--$385 if I keep the IQ sight.

Subtract $30 off these prices if you meet me locally in SW OKC.

Thanks for looking.  Call or text REDACTED.
